values: Less than a month to Scotland! Yay!!!!

The wild irises are growing again, and the exciting thing is that there are even more of them now than there were last summer! Each day they grow a little taller and more come up from the ground and I skip a few steps in anticipation of their glowing purple and gold beauty. I love Spring!



(on a side note... if I ever, ever get married, - with three weddings to attend this spring alone, I am getting impatient- I want irises in my bouquet and my colours to be shimmery medium blue and purple).

Is the adage "three times a bridesmaid, never a bride" true? I'm really hoping not because I will be a bridesmaid for the third time in May. *mentally lights a firecracker under Ryan's chair*
I just sold my soul away to more college loans. I dislike school quite a lot right now. Loans are of the devil.
Has anyone heard from Cynthia lately?

I am thankful for so many things this year. A tremendous boyfriend, a great family, terrific friends and work, an adorable dog, being able to mostly pay bills and still be decently secure about those I can't yet pay, and getting a car! Thank
Beth, Steve, and Elijah are coming to visit Friday! Can't wait!!
I'm an aunt! Beth and Steve had their first child, Elijah Miguel, on August 1 at around 2:02 our time. He weighs in at 9 pounds, 6 ounces- eesh! I can't wait to see pictures!

More and more I want to name my first daughter Grace.

I spoke today with the lady again and she told me she has been talking with her friend and agreed to use a scratch removal kit and only replace her license plate frame (which was plastic anyway) because she will probably have something similar only worse happen in the next six months, being accident prone, and I have been keeping her up to date on all the possibilities my parents and I have come up with for taking care of paying her for damages. In sum, she is calling this all off.

HALLELUJAH!

I rear-ended someone today in my friend Tara's car, which I had borrowed to return a movie. I was backing up in a driveway to let this guy on a bike get past me. While I had been waiting to make a left-hand turn out of this driveway, a car had pulled in behind me, which surprised me because the parking lot was pretty empty. Unfortunately, I didn't know it had pulled behind me until I heard Tara's car bump into it and saw the jaw of the bike guy drop. Fortunately, the driver was pretty nice about it, saying this happens to her two to three times a year. I gave her my number and driver's license number and when I got home I called her so she would know the number I gave her was legit and she offered to send me a copy of the estimate so she gave me her e-mail address so I could e-mail her my mailing address. And, there were only a few scratches on her front bumper... hopefully that means the estimate isn't too high. Sigh. Other than this, my day has been great!

I am so sorry this is belated, I was thinking about you both on Saturday though!

HAPPY BIRTHDAY, CYNTHIA AND KELSEY!!!!! I hope your birthdays were great!

My dad has yet again lost another job and it is fear for what retaliation might ensue and destroy him further that refrains me from calling his former school and giving the principal a tongue lashing she will not quickly forget. I'd also like to kick her in the shin for good measure. He is nearly 60 for Pete's sake, and already just starting over in careers! He does not need this. Of course, I am speaking from my limited human understanding and I know that God will provide something else more suited for him and I didn't like how the school he was with took advantage of and ran over the teachers and he had only been there a year and was planning on leaving anyway to do student teaching for his credentialing programme (blasted APU, wanting eighteen weeks of full time student teaching... hang high standards! Why can't it be like Cal Baptist which requires fourteen weeks of part time student teaching? :-)~ ), but that was to be in September and this is mid-Spring semester of all the possible times to let three teachers go! Way to screw yourself and the remaining teachers over, as well as your former employees! I am thankful that my mom has a part time job, as does Daniel, so Deej at least can pay for some of the things he wants, like lunch at school and new skateboards, but if the dental insurance does not carry through for the next month, my family will have to pay full price for Deej's wisdom teeth removal and Mom's crown replacement and possible gum graft. Woot. And I still owe my parents bunches for paying my credit card bills... *guilt* Fortunately, he has started right away in pursuing job options and hopefully something will work out soon. My worry is that he won't be able to focus on his classwork and will struggle in his classes- however, now he has more time to work on his assignments. Hmmm...

I was correcting midterm essays for Level 5 students at work today and got curious about their assigned topic, which was to consider the International Justice Mission work of rescuing children from forced prostitution and slavery, or to write about legalizing prostitution and take a stance on either topic (they had researched the latter already, the topic being one they chose to research as a class for the semester and practice their writing skills with). Curious about something Michael, their instructor, had told me about as he was explaining what I should look for, I spent the last few minutes at work reading an article and commentaries on the subject.

Here's some of what I found:

http://www.prostitucio.hu/janice.raymond.2004.05.28.en.htm

http://hortensia.ca/Prostitution/Prostitution_germany.htm

http://www.freedominion.ca/phpBB2/viewtopic.php?t=36344&postdays=0&postorder=asc&start=0

I can't find the original article that I found at work, but one of these reacts to it, where a woman in Germany seeking employment was referred to a position as a prostitute by an unemployment agency and was threatened with the revoking of her unemployment benefits if she did not take the job. That made my heart sick as I read, and yet it is not enough to have an emotional reaction. I want to go out and pummel some a** of those in Germany who thought legalizing prostitution would increase the safety of the prostitutes and decrease the amount of crime. Were they truly thinking compassionately and with everyone's best interests in mind, or were they hoping to have their personal sins of participation in prostitution legally absolved? Bah!

growing strongly, ever stronger

loving deeply, ever deeper

"To laugh often and much; to win the respect of intelligent people and the affection of children; to earn the appreciation of honest critics and endure the betrayal of false friends; to appreciate beauty, to find the best in others; to leave the world a little better; to know even one life has breathed easier because you have lived. This is the meaning of success." - Emerson

I am through with school, fianlly. This was not a satisfying semester, academically. I didn't fail any of my courses, but I did not give them the attention they deserved. As one of my professors commented in the middle of the term, I was distracted and distant. I haven't paid proper attention to anyone in so long, not even myself, but where my attention went I do not know. There have been so many people (at least for me) to keep involved with along with schoolwork, work, my grandfather and family... Now I have a month before summer camp begins and a different type of insanity starts. In the meantime, I am finishing a quilt I began in junior high that Mom found while cleaning her sewing room, helping out with the junior high group at church, hopefully riding my bike every day, sleeping in, prepping for camp and a little for next semester, cleaning, reading, and trying to find a focus again. I have been a little out of sorts, sometimes more than other times, all semester. Nice time to be in a funk. :) I have had wonderful times too, but joining the junior high group tonight reminded me how out of touch I am with parts of my world that I used to be so involved in. I hate losing touch with people and activities that I used to hold dear. *sigh* Not an entirely lackluster day, for all of that. I read some of The Sword in the Stone this morning, watched The Adventures of Tom & Huck (yes, I am aware that came out when we were in junior high and was a kid's movie even then), and burned cds for Mom at the church office. I also flirted, lightly, with Josh, the worship and junior high leader. It is nice to be noticed, even if it is by a guy who shoots staples at you across a room and flirts more with Kayla. I never would pursue something with Josh, but he can be fun and he is very gifted vocally and artistically (*envious*). I should get going to bed... sigh. Sleep is wonderful. :)

Your brain: 100% interpersonal, 120% visual, 80% verbal, and 100% mathematical!
Congratulations on being 400% smart! Actually, on my test, everyone is. The above score breaks down what kind of thinking you most enjoy doing. A score above 100% means you use that kind of thinking more than average, and a score below 100% means you use it less. It says nothing about how good you are at any one, just how interested you are in each, relatively. A substantial difference in scores between two people means, conclusively, that they are different kinds of thinkers.

Matching Summary: Each of us has different tastes. Still, I offer the following advice, which I think is obvious:

  1. Don't date someone if your interpersonal percentages differ by more than 80%.
  2. Don't be friends with someone if your verbal percentages differ by more than 100%.
  3. Don't have sex with someone if their math percentage is over 200%.

Today. Today was a blast. I think Ryan is getting used to my being quiet when I am content and not questioning why I don't talk very much, just smile at everything. He was quiet too. And the garden. Amazing. Tranquil, even with so many people meandering through it. Lovely koto music, good dancing, and terrific drum playing (I forget what the name is of that style of playing). Yummy tea also. It was good to be with him, watching the koi and laughing/admiring/learning about them, learning about Japanese gardening methods, following the butterflies as best as I could without running after them, and... if he ever reads this he will probably laugh because it will be overkill for him... there were so many adorable little kids everywhere. One, about one and half or two toddled to his father, who was lying on his back on the grass, and fell on top of him. Then, as his parents started to leave, he walked to the red wagon pulled by his mother and tumbled in, faceplanting in something soft. There were a couple babies being carried in the baby slings that remind me of the way Nigerian mothers carry babies and how Mom carried Beth and me when we were babies, only the ones today were across the chest and Mom had us on her back.

We went to dinner afterwards and shared drinking stories from our study abroad times. Drinking games can get ugly. I had a chicken pot pie, which reminds me both of Cornish pasties and the Scottish meat pies Grandpa would sometimes bring when he would visit us from Florida (we found an ad while we were there for a British shop that sells Scotch meat pies, but it was the day we were leaving. But we have the ad still, so something needs to be done with it. Maybe in the month before camp...). I was just reminded how hard it is sometimes to be home, and in the most routine actions. Setting the table, I take out enough dishes for five settings if I don't think about it. After dinner, I half expect to go into the family room and turn on the tv to sports for Grandpa, or expect to hear it playing and when I enter to see him sitting in his chair. Entering the living room from the front door, I instinctively turn to the chair in the corner to greet him. Helping Mom paint his room this month will be strange.

Anyway, we also went to see Hitchhiker's, completely forgetting bathrobes and towels in attempts to get inside the theatre in time. Then, when we drove home, we talked about the movies The Lion the Witch and the Wardrobe, Kingdom of Heaven, Lord of the Rings, and Arthur (fears that KoH will be like Arthur in stinktified history or that the fanatical Christians will be all the ones killing, and LOTR, particularly Legolas being made into fan fodder, and noting that fantasy movies based on books are getting even more popular). That ended up in a discussion about the wonders of the Irish, mostly Turkey talking and me nodding in agreement then my laughing at the Miller/Budweiser billboards by the Miller brewery while he was talking about the Gangs of New York soundtrack that was playing. He joined Amy and me for Death by Chocolate, then left to drive home.

(*my mood is naughty because I am procrastinating, and don't want to study for any of my finals, but I will be screwed if I don't*)

The Word of the Day for Apr 09 is:  
vermicular \ver-MIK-yuh-ler\ adjective 

1 *a : resembling a worm in form or motion b : marked with irregular fine lines or with wavy impressed lines 
2 : of, relating to, or caused by worms 
 
 
Example sentence:
"[The painting] 'Evening' shows what was likely a meandering stream that in Criss's treatment is less vermicular than just plain geometric." (Susan Lindt, Intelligencer Journal [Lancaster, PA], July 3, 2003) 
 
Did you know?
What does the word "vermicular" have in common with the pasta on your plate? If you're eating vermicelli (a spaghetti-like pasta made in long thin strings) the answer is "vermis," a Latin noun meaning "worm." If you dig deep enough, you'll find that "vermis" is the root underlying not only "vermicular" and "vermicelli," but also "vermiculate" (which can mean either "full of worms" or "tortuous") and even "worm" itself.

*Indicates the sense illustrated in the example sentence.

The Word of the Day for Mar 31 is:  
contiguous \kun-TIG-yuh-wus\ adjective 

: being in contact : touching; also : next, adjoining 
 
 
Example sentence:
The new airline will fly to all of the 48 contiguous states in the United States, but it will not have any flights to Alaska or Hawaii. 
 
Did you know?
You probably aren't surprised to learn that the word "contact" is a relative of "contiguous," but would you believe that "contagion" and "contingent" are too? All of those words derive from the Latin "contingere," meaning "to have contact with." The words "contact" and "contiguous" are fairly easy to connect with "contingere," but what of the other two? In its early days in English, "contingent" was used as a synonym of "touching," and if you remember that touching something can pollute it (and that another meaning of "contingere" was "to pollute"), "contagion" logically ties in too.
